{
  "updated_summary": "In a traditional Japanese dining room with tatami mats and wooden decor, a group including the Man in Blue Shirt with Headband, the Woman in Yellow Dress, and the Man in Blue T-Shirt gathered around a low wooden table laden with blue-and-white patterned bowls, plates of mochi, natto, and broth. The meal began with a chef preparing sautéed grasshoppers, cleaned and stir-fried in a homemade teriyaki sauce of sugar, soy sauce, and sake. The Man in Blue Shirt with Headband was offered the grasshoppers, with encouragement to try them, while the Woman in Yellow Dress expressed hesitation and another man humorously advised against looking at them. The Woman in Green Cardigan exclaimed \"Delicious!\" in Japanese. The Man in Blue Shirt with Headband, after examining a grasshopper with chopsticks, declared he would try it and, to traditional Japanese music, took a bite, describing the experience as surprisingly good, sweet, salty, crunchy, and papery, with no gooiness. The Woman in Yellow Dress agreed it was \"not bad.\" Later, the group examined mochi topped with natto; the Man in Blue Shirt with Headband noted its fermented smell but was surprised by its stringiness, describing it as \"slime on slime crime,\" while the Woman in Yellow Dress found it appealing and mentioned its commonality in Japanese breakfasts. A gong sound signaled the arrival of fried mochi coated in breadcrumbs and a dark sauce, which the Man in Blue Shirt with Headband identified as dessert. The Woman in Yellow Dress found it a \"chewy mouthful\" and \"good stuff,\" and the Man in Blue Shirt with Headband described its texture as sticky, a little sweet, nutty, and earthy, with the Woman in Yellow Dress confirming the nutty flavor."
."
